VALUES
(40, 12, 26, 43, 14, 30, 30, 'his kingdom stand', 'Connection of Kingdom and Authority', 'This connection highlights the concept of authority and power. In Matthew, the division of Satan''s kingdom suggests a struggle for dominance, while in John, the reference to the ''prince of this world'' indicates a similar theme of opposing forces in the spiritual realm.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 26, 47, 4, 4, 4, 'divided against himself', 'Division and Blindness in Belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of division within opposing forces. In Matthew, the idea of a divided kingdom suggests internal conflict, while in 2 Corinthians, the ''god of this world'' blinding minds indicates a spiritual opposition to the truth.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 27, 41, 9, 38, 39, 'cast out devils', 'Authority Over Demons', 'This connection highlights the authority to cast out devils. Both passages emphasize the act of casting out demons in Jesus'' name, suggesting a shared power among His followers.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 27, 44, 19, 13, 16, 'by whom do your children cast them out', 'Authority Over Evil Spirits', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in casting out evil spirits. In Matthew, Jesus challenges the legitimacy of exorcists by questioning their source of power, while in Acts, the vagabond Jews attempt to invoke Jesus'' name without true authority, leading to their failure.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 27, 42, 9, 49, 50, NULL, 'Authority Over Demons', 'This connection highlights the theme of casting out devils. Both passages address the authority to expel demons, with Matthew questioning the source of power and Luke affirming that those who act in Jesus'' name are on His side.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 27, 42, 11, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Casting Out Devils', 'Both passages emphasize the challenge to the authority of Jesus by questioning the source of His power to cast out devils. The similar phrasing regarding ''your sons'' indicates a direct parallel in the argument presented.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 27, 45, 3, 19, 19, 'therefore they shall be your judges', 'Judgment and Accountability', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and accountability before God. In Matthew, the reference to judges implies a standard of righteousness, while Romans emphasizes that all are guilty under the law, indicating a universal accountability.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 27, 40, 12, 41, 42, NULL, 'Judgment and Repentance Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment, as both passages discuss how certain groups will rise in judgment against the current generation. The mention of repentance in the Nineveh passage parallels the implied judgment against those who do not recognize Jesus'' authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 28, 42, 11, 20, 20, 'kingdom of God is come', 'Connection of Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize the arrival of the kingdom of God through the act of casting out devils. The phrases ''kingdom of God is come unto you'' and ''kingdom of God is come upon you'' highlight this thematic link.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 28, 27, 7, 14, 14, 'kingdom of God is come unto you', 'Connection of Kingdom and Authority', 'This connection highlights the establishment of God''s kingdom through Jesus'' authority over evil. Both passages emphasize the dominion and everlasting nature of the kingdom, linking Jesus'' actions to the prophetic vision in Daniel.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 28, 40, 6, 33, 33, 'kingdom of God', 'Kingdom of God Connection', 'This connection highlights the importance of the kingdom of God in both passages. In Matthew 12:28, the arrival of the kingdom is linked to the casting out of devils, while Matthew 6:33 emphasizes seeking the kingdom first.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 28, 44, 10, 38, 38, 'by the Spirit of God', 'Connection of Divine Power', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Holy Spirit in Jesus'' ministry, highlighting how He cast out devils and healed the oppressed. This connection illustrates the manifestation of God''s kingdom through Jesus'' actions empowered by the Spirit.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 28, 40, 21, 43, 43, 'the kingdom of God', 'Connection of the Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of the kingdom of God. The first passage indicates its arrival through the casting out of devils, while the second suggests its transfer to a new nation that produces fruit.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 28, 51, 1, 13, 13, 'kingdom of God', 'Kingdom of God Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of the kingdom of God. Both passages emphasize the transition from darkness to the kingdom, indicating a spiritual authority and deliverance.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 28, 41, 1, 15, 15, 'kingdom of God is come unto you', 'Kingdom of God Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the arrival of the kingdom of God. Matthew highlights its presence through the casting out of devils, while Mark declares its nearness and calls for repentance.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 29, 23, 49, 24, 24, 'strong man', 'Connection of Strength and Deliverance', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of overcoming a strong adversary to achieve deliverance. Matthew speaks of binding the strong man to spoil his house, while Isaiah questions whether the mighty can be defeated to rescue captives.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 29, 41, 3, 27, 27, NULL, 'Connection of Strong Man Concept', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of binding the strong man before spoiling his house. This parallel structure highlights a shared teaching about overcoming opposition.', 'parallel', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 29, 42, 11, 21, 22, 'strong man', 'Connection of Strong Man Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a ''strong man'' and the necessity of overcoming him to take his goods. This connection highlights the idea of binding or overcoming a strong figure to access what he possesses.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 29, 62, 4, 4, 4, 'bind the strong man', 'Overcoming the Strong Man', 'This connection highlights the theme of overcoming powerful adversaries. In Matthew, binding the strong man represents overcoming evil, while in 1 John, the greater one within believers signifies their victory over worldly forces.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 29, 66, 20, 7, 9, 'bind the strong man', 'Binding and Deception Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of binding the strong man, which is reflected in Satan''s eventual release to deceive the nations. Both passages emphasize the power dynamics involved in spiritual warfare and the ultimate defeat of evil.', 'theme', 0.37, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 29, 62, 3, 8, 8, 'bind the strong man', 'Binding the Strong Man', 'This connection highlights the theme of overcoming evil. In Matthew, binding the strong man represents the need to confront and defeat evil forces, while 1 John emphasizes that the Son of God was manifested to destroy the works of the devil.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 29, 23, 53, 12, 12, 'spoil his house', 'Connection of Spoiling and Strong', 'This connection highlights the theme of ''spoil'' and ''strong.'' In Matthew, the strong man must be bound to spoil his house, while Isaiah speaks of dividing the spoil with the strong, indicating a shared concept of overcoming strength to achieve victory.', 'theme', 0.349, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 30, 41, 9, 40, 40, NULL, 'Contrasting Views on Allegiance', 'This connection highlights differing perspectives on allegiance to Jesus. Matthew emphasizes a binary stance of being either with or against, while Mark suggests a more inclusive view that those not opposing are allies.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 30, 42, 11, 23, 23, 'He that is not with me is against me', 'Connection of Opposition and Gathering', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that those who are not aligned with Jesus are considered against him. Additionally, they highlight the importance of gathering with him rather than scattering.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 30, 6, 24, 15, 15, 'He that is not with me is against me', 'Choice and Allegiance to God', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of choosing sides in relation to God. Matthew highlights the division between those who are with Christ and those who are against Him, while Joshua calls for a decision on whom to serve.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 30, 42, 9, 50, 50, 'he that is not with me is against me', 'Unity in Christ''s Mission', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that one''s stance towards Jesus defines their alignment. Matthew highlights that those not with Him are against Him, while Luke suggests that those not against Him are for Him, illustrating a shared theme of allegiance.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 30, 62, 2, 19, 19, 'He that is not with me is against me', 'Divisive Nature of Allegiance', 'This connection highlights the theme of division based on allegiance. Both passages emphasize that those who do not align with the truth ultimately reveal their true nature.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 30, 40, 6, 24, 24, 'he that is not with me is against me', 'Serving Two Masters', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of loyalty, stating that one cannot be neutral. Matthew 12:30 highlights the division between those who gather with Christ and those who scatter, while Matthew 6:24 underscores the impossibility of serving both God and mammon.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 30, 47, 6, 15, 16, 'He that is not with me', 'Alignment of Belief and Action', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of alignment with Christ. Matthew highlights that one must be with Him or against Him, while 2 Corinthians contrasts believers with infidels, stressing the importance of unity in faith.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 31, 42, 12, 10, 10, 'blasphemy against the Holy Ghost', 'Blasphemy Against the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize that blasphemy against the Holy Ghost is unforgivable. This connection highlights the severity of this specific sin in contrast to other forms of blasphemy.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
